result.execSummary:
Victor M. Hernandez was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Victor M. Hernandez was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Victor M. Hernandez in court, in custody with attorney Bradley J Jansen.  Robert G. Barrington appeared for the State of Wisconsin. State heard on gov's warrant; discussion held; Atty Jansen heard and def will waive extradition
Extradition hearing on June 4, 2015 at 10:00 am.

(9:50) Defendant Victor M. Hernandez in court, in custody with attorney Bradley J Jansen.  Robert G. Barrington appeared for the State of Wisconsin. This is extradition initial/rights hearing; complaint reviewed; Court reviews Def.'s rights; Def. wanted in State of Texas; Atty. Jansen heard - Def. is requesting Gov. Warrant; bail is not an option in this case (possible life in prison); Court finds PC that Def. is person wanted in Texas; Def. to be held without bail at the Dodge County Jail; Extradition hearing scheduled; Def. remanded
